reason_thou:
1. Understanding the Issue:
The provided IR causes opt --passes=slp-vectorizer to abort with a malloc(): corrupted top size error. This strongly indicates a heap corruption (out-of-bounds write or excessive allocation) rather than a logical assertion failure. The crash backtrace points into BoUpSLP::processBuildVector(), specifically the lambda TryPackScalars (frame at line ~16250). That lambda manipulates SmallVector<Value*> Scalars and a parallel mask vector (ReuseMask). If it writes beyond the allocated mask storage or appends an absurd number of elements, the heap can be corrupted leading to the later glibc abort.

2. Analyzing opt's Log:
The log shows a gather node with 12 scalar values (select instructions). The vectorizer computes a cost and a tree size reported as 6: "Calculating cost for tree of size 6." This implies E->getVectorFactor() (VF) is 6 while E->Scalars.size() is 12 in this gather node. Later the vectorization tries to build a vector for these 12 scalars using a VF of 6. That is an unusual but apparently reachable configuration (vector factor smaller than number of gathered scalars due to reuse/shuffle decisions). The first transformation happens inside processBuildVector when constructing shuffle/gather patterns.

3. Root Cause Analysis:
In processBuildVector, the lambda TryPackScalars (lines 16243–16282 original) begins by unconditionally executing:
  Scalars.append(VF - Scalars.size(), PoisonValue::get(OrigScalarTy));
This assumes VF >= Scalars.size(). In our reproducer VF == 6 and Scalars.size() == 12. Since both are unsigned, VF - Scalars.size() underflows, producing a very large unsigned value. SmallVector then tries to append that many PoisonValue entries, corrupting memory (or triggering enormous allocation attempts). Even if Scalars.size() were only slightly larger than VF, subsequent loops would write ReuseMask[I] for I >= ReuseMask.size() (the mask is not resized after the append), causing out-of-bounds writes. Thus the root cause is the missing guard ensuring VF >= Scalars.size() (an invariant that does not always hold) and failing to keep ReuseMask sized consistently with Scalars after modification.
The code earlier in processBuildVector conditionally pads when GatheredScalars.size() != VF and size < VF, but there is no analogous handling for size > VF. Hence TryPackScalars is invoked in an unsupported state.

4. Proposed Edit Point(s):
Edit lines 16243–16252 (definition start of TryPackScalars and the unconditional append) to make appending conditional and to keep the ReuseMask vector in sync, avoiding unsigned underflow and mask overruns.
Concrete change:
Replace the unconditional append line with guarded logic:
  if (Scalars.size() < VF) {
    unsigned OldSize = Scalars.size();
    Scalars.append(VF - OldSize, PoisonValue::get(OrigScalarTy));
    if (ReuseMask.size() < Scalars.size())
      ReuseMask.resize(Scalars.size(), PoisonMaskElem);
  } else {
    // VF < Scalars.size(): do not append; ensure mask covers all scalars.
    if (ReuseMask.size() < Scalars.size())
      ReuseMask.resize(Scalars.size(), PoisonMaskElem);
  }

Optionally we could add a comment documenting that VF may be less than Scalars.size() for certain gather reuse patterns and that later logic iterates over full Scalars length.
This prevents underflow, huge allocation and mask OOB writes while preserving existing semantics for VF >= size.

5. Conclusion:
The crash is due to unsigned underflow and subsequent memory corruption in TryPackScalars when vector factor VF is smaller than the number of gathered scalars. Adding a guard and synchronizing the mask vector fixes the heap corruption without altering higher-level vectorization decisions. After this patch, processBuildVector will safely handle cases where VF < Scalars.size(), eliminating the abort for the provided reproducer.

